  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects how many people, especially women and minorities, engage with science and technology. As a mother of three and a part-time hairdresser in New York, I've seen firsthand how fear of being judged or failing because of societal expectations can hold people back. For instance, when my daughter asks about her science project, I often hear her say, 'I don't want to be the one who's not good at math,' even though she's bright and curious. This kind of self-doubt, fueled by stereotypes, is stereotype threat in action. It's not just about individual performance; it's about the psychological weight of being labeled as 'not belonging.' We absolutely must address this. Schools and workplaces need to create inclusive environments where everyone feels safe to explore STEM without fear of judgment. This could mean mentorship programs that pair students with role models from diverse backgrounds, or workshops that teach students to challenge stereotypes early on. As someone who values community and collaboration—my hobbies include yoga and running, which emphasize mindfulness and teamwork—I believe change starts with empathy and open conversations. By fostering environments where everyone feels valued, we can break down these barriers and encourage more people to thrive in STEM fields. It's not about fixing people; it's about fixing the systems that make them feel unwelcome.",
